<TITLE> Govt, BNP end three hour dialogue </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, Oct 14 (bdnews24.com) - A three hour dialogue between the government and the BNP concluded Tuesday afternoon at the chief adviser's office. Secretary general Khandaker Delwar Hossain is leading a 13-member BNP delegation, while the government side is being led by chief adviser Fakhrudddin Ahmed and five other advisers Ghulam Quader, AFM Hassan Ariff, Iftekhar Ahmed Chowdhury, Anwarul Iqbal and Hossain Zillur Rahman joining him. The long-awaited dialogue between the government and BNP began around 11.15am and ended at 2.10pm, Md Kazi Aminul Islam, secretary to the CA's office, told bdnews24.com. The meeting was brought forward by a day. It had been originally scheduled for Oct 15. The morning talks with the BNP will be followed by an afternoon dialogue with its four-party ally, Jamaat-e-Islami. Prior to the dialogue BNP joint secretary general Nazrul Islam Khan told bdnews24.com that the discussions would focus on "some existing obstacles to holding a fair election, especially the issue of withdrawal of the state of emergency". The party would repeat the demand for withdrawal of the state of emergency, scrapping the amended Representation of the People Ordinance, and release of the party leaders in jail and withdrawal of cases against them, he said. The dialogue between the government and the political parties started on May 22. The government has already had meetings with 16 parties including the Awami League. bdnew
